Comments: While the survey should capture the highlights, it probably will not capture the whole picture. For example, a lot of money laundering is facilitated through a number of European countries so it is difficult to nominate just a couple. Likewise cybercrime as a service is aslo wide spread with RATs being produced in various countries such as the UK, the USA or Australia which are in turn used by syndicates in other countres like Nigeria or South Africa.

In a world where Crime as a Service is becoming prevalent, it is hard to attribute single regions or countries to specific crime types. With the crime often originating in one and utilising another to realise the economic gain.

Comments: Really interesting project! My biggest comment is about the ambiguousness of the final category (cashing out/money laundering). I was a bit confused about how I should be responding to this one, whether the responses should refer to the locations of the money mules or the locations of the actors utilizing the money mules. I used the locations of the actors using the mules in my response for this one, but I could easily see others having similar confusion since this category is inherently different from the other four (the first four categories refer to the primary attack, while cashing out is generally a secondary step AFTER an attack).

you need to look at cyber and geography in a different way in my view. The point is not so much about cyber criminals from one region praying on victims in another its more about geo strategic conditions facilitating cyber crime within a region. So for example the biggest example of this is cyber insurance and GDPR in western countries being exploited by criminals outside of these regions. In this case its no so much where the criminals are but who they are targeting - I think that is different in my view from the question y'all are investigating.

Comments: Comment - in interpreting the data you receive it would probably be helpful to also consider the cultures of the areas committing the crimes in order to inform you analysis.  For example, Africa is big on advanced fee & BEC scams while Eurasia tends to see more organized crime models (ransomware / credit card skimming / etc).   Those development are largely cultural and serve as the basis for why we don't see ransomware coming out of Africa... cultural incongruity.
I answered the money laundering questions regarding the countries that are used for cashing out. This does not mean that the actual threat actors live there.

Expert_crimetype: Technical products / services,Attacks and extortions,Data/identity theft,Scams,Cashing out/money laundering
Comments: Mainly I pick on Russia and Nigeria for being major sources of severely impactful crime. This is because they are at both extreme ends of the spectrum - in Russia the government ultimately controls it all, leading to a high level of competency and professionalism. Where as in Nigeria the government has zero control over the situation, leading to a high impact but very low levels of technical ability and professionalism. Ultimately though, the only people who can stop the crime are exactly those people - the governments. And what you're looking at here is both high levels of motivation to keep it going and low levels of motivation to stop it.

Technical products / services,Attacks and extortions,Data/identity theft
Comments:
As an analyst, it's often difficult to know where a cybercriminal is located. Often our best hints (in my field of threat intelligence) are language based, and languages like Russian are spoken in multiple countries, while English is spoke by native and second language speakers around the world. It's difficult to pinpoint. 

For me, I think some interesting answers to this survey may be lost by the inclusion of the word "significant" in the questions. For instance, Brazil is a cybercriminal powerhouse in Latin America. But on a global scale, it is by no means a "significant" source of any type of cybercrime, so I never included it in my answers. It's not top 5, but its number 1 in the region and is definitely what I would describe as a "cybercriminal hub."

Comments:
I only responded to questions where I knew an answer.
If I replied Lebanon, it is actually the region, they replace crime in the former East European region, especially financial crime, mules, money laundering.
The same is valid for Nigiera it is the region around the country. And the criminals often act out of other place like ZA or the UK. But they also work global ie in the field of dating services (identity theft, fraud...)
North Korea and China are of course of interest. Both in the field of IP crime and political engagement, but I personally don't know enough about these two countries.
In summary, I don't believe you can use a categorization by country. It is more likely that criminals act in specific crime areas, but all over the place.
However, the use of lack of legislation in specific countries is obvious.
